The only non-terminal that can produce the terminal symbol ‘t7’ is NT22, because the grammar contains the rule

 NT22 → 't7'

and no other rule produces ‘t7’.  
Hence the first word of any derivation for the given string must come from a subtree whose leftmost leaf is produced by NT22.

In Chomsky normal form a node that produces more than one terminal symbol must do so through a rule of the form

 X → NT22 Y

where Y is some non-terminal whose first terminal leaf will become the second word of the string.  
The grammar contains exactly four binary rules whose left child is NT22:

 NT7  → NT22 NT5  
 NT8  → NT22 NT9  
 NT21 → NT22 NT23  
 NT26 → NT22 NT12  

Therefore, in every possible derivation the second word of the string must be the first word produced by NT5, NT9, NT23 or NT12 respectively.

But the first terminals producible by these four non-terminals are:

• NT5  → 't6'                                 (only)  
• NT9  → 't12'  or  't16'  
• NT23 → 't23', 't4', 't21', or a word generated via NT19 (='t22') followed by at least one further
           symbol (since NT23 → NT19 NT8 and NT8 always produces at least one terminal)  
• NT12 → 't0' (via NT26) or 't15'/'t23'/… but never a single, isolated 't22'
           (NT12 → NT29 NT6 or NT26 NT21, both giving a first word other than 't22').

Consequently none of these possibilities yields ‘t22’ as the immediate successor of the initial ‘t7’.  
Hence no derivation in the grammar can begin with the two-word prefix “t7 t22”.

Because the target string starts with exactly that prefix, the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, every derivation of the 21-token string must correspond to a binary parse tree whose internal nodes are produced by the two-non-terminal rules listed, while every leaf is generated by one of the single-terminal rules.

Step 1 – leaves  
For every individual token in the string we list the non-terminals that can produce it.  
(The only ones that appear are shown below.)

t9  → NT11  
t15 → NT24, NT29, NT2  
t2  → NT10  
t13 → NT19, NT11  
t7  → NT22  
t1  → NT25  
t14 → NT31, NT17, NT32  
t23 → NT23  
t17 → NT4  
t8  → NT21  
t16 → NT7, NT9, NT4  
t3  → NT16, NT20  
t18 → NT6, NT32  
t5  → NT19  

Step 2 – length-2 substrings  
Using all binary rules A → BC we compute which non-terminals can cover every two-token substring.  The only successful pairs that arise are

• NT22  covers positions 13-14 (t16 t15) via the rule NT22 → NT9 NT24  
• NT0   covers positions 19-20 (t3 t3)  via the rule NT0 → NT20 NT16  

Every other two-token substring admits no binary combination of the grammar’s rules.

Step 3 – longer substrings  
Building on the only two successful length-2 results, we try to extend them:

• No rule combines NT22 with the symbol sets that occur immediately to its left or right, so no non-terminal can cover any substring that contains positions 13-14 and is longer than two tokens.

• NT0 cannot be joined with the non-terminal sets occurring on its left or right either, so it too cannot participate in a larger constituent (except the trivial two-token one already found).

As a consequence, when we attempt to cover any substring of length ≥ 3, every required split fails: no pair (B,C) generated by the grammar matches the non-terminal sets available on the left and right halves.  In particular, no non-terminal—certainly not S—can be placed over the complete 21-token string (there is no successful way to span even the first three tokens).

Step 4 – root symbol  
Because the start symbol S can only be introduced by one of its own three rules
   S → NT11 NT0 | S → NT1 NT12 | S → NT16 NT12
the left half of the input would have to be generated by NT11, NT1 or NT16 and the right half by NT0 or NT12.  The analysis above shows that neither half of the string can be covered by those non-terminals (or by any other), so S cannot derive the entire string.

Conclusion  
No complete binary parse exists for the 21-token input.  Hence the string is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No

The only non-terminal that can generate the terminal symbol t17 is NT4, via the rule

    NT4 → 't17'

Examining all rules that can place NT4 at the leftmost position of the sentential form shows that the unique way to have t17 as the first symbol produced by S is

    S  ⇒ NT16 NT12
    NT16 ⇒ NT4 NT14
    NT4 ⇒ 't17'

Hence, after t17 the next symbol in the derived string must be the first symbol generated by NT14.

The possible first symbols produced by NT14 are limited to the terminals that can start any of the right-hand sides of its productions:

    NT14 → 't6'                       (starts with t6)
    NT14 → NT1 NT16                   (starts with whatever NT1 can start with)
    NT14 → NT1 NT7                    (starts with whatever NT1 can start with)
    NT14 → NT2 NT29                   (starts with whatever NT2 can start with)
    NT14 → NT32 NT12                  (starts with whatever NT32 can start with)

A detailed inspection of all productions for NT1, NT2 and NT32 shows that their leftmost derivable terminals are confined to
t6, t10, t12, t14, t15, t18, t19, t22, t3, t5, t7, t8, and t0  
—none of which is t16.

Therefore NT14 can never derive a string whose first terminal is t16.  But the target string has t16 as its second symbol:

    t17  t16  …

Hence no derivation from S can yield the required prefix “t17 t16”, and consequently the whole string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

Despite several promising local matches (e.g. tokens 1–2   NT1, 2–5   NT0, 11–12  NT7, etc.), no combination of the available binary productions lets these constituents be assembled into any of the three possible top-level patterns for the start symbol S (S → NT11 NT0, S → NT1 NT12, or S → NT16 NT12).  
In particular:

• For S → NT11 NT0 the right-hand NT0 must end with an NT7 (because NT0 → NT3 NT7 is the only rule allowing the final terminal t16).  The substring ending in t16 is either “t22 t16” or “t14 t22 t16”, but none of them can be generated by NT0 because NT3 cannot yield the required preceding sequence of terminals.

• For S → NT1 NT12 and S → NT16 NT12, the suffix NT12 would have to generate a string whose last symbol is t16.  Every derivation of NT12 ultimately ends in either NT6 or NT21, and neither of these non-terminals can derive any word ending in t16 (NT6’s terminals are t10/t18 or pairs ending in t14/t22; NT21’s terminals are t4/t8 or longer words ending in neither t16 nor a symbol that could reduce to it).

Since none of the three possible shapes of a complete derivation works, the string cannot be produced by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can only expand to one of three binary forms:
① S → NT11 NT0
② S → NT1  NT12
③ S → NT16 NT12

Hence any successful derivation must split the 19-token string into two contiguous blocks whose left block derives NT11 / NT1 / NT16 and whose right block derives NT0 / NT12 respectively.

Working bottom-up (CYK style) from the 19 single-token substrings:

• Every token was replaced by all pre-terminals that can emit that terminal.  
• All length-2 substrings were then checked against every binary rule in the grammar.  
  – Only three length-2 combinations are possible:  
    positions 3-4 → NT19 (t1 t15)  
    positions 17-18 → NT20 (t8 t22)  
    positions 18-19 → NT7 (t22 t22)  
• From these we obtain the only length-3 constituent:  
  positions 17-19 → NT30  (since NT20 NT17 = NT30, taking NT17 from the second t22).  
  No other length-3 or larger constituents can be produced; in particular no substring yields NT0 or NT12 at any length, and none yields NT11, NT1, or NT16 as required on the left side of S.

Because neither half of any possible top-level split can derive the non-terminals demanded by S’s productions, the entire 19-token string cannot be generated by the grammar.

Therefore the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The only start-productions for S are  

1. S → NT11 NT0  
2. S → NT1  NT12  
3. S → NT16 NT12  

The string begins with the terminal t5.
Among the three left-hand non-terminals (NT11, NT1, NT16) only NT11 can start with t5:

• NT11 → NT19 NT13  
  NT19 → 't5'     NT13 → 't6'  

so the first two terminals (“t5 t6”) must be produced by NT11.
Hence the rest of the string (the remaining 28 terminals beginning with t18)
has to be generated by NT0, because the start production must be
S → NT11 NT0.

But NT0 has only two forms:

a) NT0 → 't10'           (single terminal t10)  
b) NT0 → NT20 NT16      (two non-terminals; the first symbol is produced by NT20)

Therefore any string derived from NT0 either

• is exactly “t10”, or  
• begins with whatever NT20 can start with.

Examine NT20’s possibilities:

NT20 → 't3'                (starts with t3)  
NT20 → NT25 NT19     (NT25 ⇒ t1, so starts with t1)  
NT20 → NT0  NT28     (NT0 ⇒ t10 or starts with the same options as above, so starts with t10, t3 or t1)  
NT20 → NT21 NT15    (NT21 ⇒ t8 or t4, so starts with t8 or t4)

Consequently every string derived from NT20—and hence every string derived from NT0—must start with one of
t10, t3, t1, t8, or t4.

The substring that NT0 must generate starts with t18, which is none of these.
Hence NT0 cannot generate the required 28-symbol suffix,
so NT11 NT0 cannot generate the whole 30-symbol string,
and the other two start rules are ruled out (their left parts cannot start with t5).

Therefore the grammar does not generate the given string.
